    "millsfield:images_texts": [
      "First Regular Passenger Service\nJune 22, 1910 • Friedrichshafen, Germany\n10F\nREPUBLIQUE DE HAUTE-VOLTA\n80\nBRICHS\n22.-6.84-12\n7990\nEICHSHAN\n: 22-6.84-12\n7990",
      "International Tributes to the History of Flight\nFirst Regular Passenger Service\nAlthough three of his first four lighter-than-air craft\nThe full color cachet shows one of the passenger\nwere disappointments,\nCount Ferdinand von Zep-\nZeppelins sailing through the skies at about 45 miles\npelin remained an optimist. In 1909, he organized\nper hour. DELAG airships were outfitted with carpets\nthe\nDeutsche\nLuftschiffarhts-Aktiengesellschaft\nand wicker armchairs. Cold lunches and wine were\n(DELAG), with the idea of starting the world's first\nserved to travelers during the flight.\npassenger airline.\nIn 1910, the LZ-7 \"Deutschland\" was flown from\nthe Zeppelin works in Friedrichshafen to Dusseldorf.\nThere, on June 22, passenger service was officially\ninaugurated with flights to Frankfurt and Baden-\nMint Stamp: The mint stamp on this Cover, showing\nthe \"Deutschland\" in flight over Friedrichshafen, was\nissued by Upper Volta in 1976. In the background is\nLake Constance (Bodensee), a popular resort area.\nBaden. Soon several more Zeppelins were added to\nthe fleet, and the service linked most of Germany's\nmajor cities. Before World\nWar 1,\nDELAG had\nflown 34,228 passengers over 107,213 miles — with-\nout an injury or fatality.\nPostmark: This Cover was postmarked in Friedrichs-\nhafen, Germany on June 22, 1984, the exact anni-\nversary of the inauguration of the first passenger\nservice.\n© Postal Commemorative Society\nPrinted in U.S.A.\nW19. 0960.021"
    ],
